metadata.title: Cessna 182 Skylane
aws::graph::propositions: # Cessna 182 Skylane Model History and Features
The 1971 model year of Cessna 182 Skylane introduced shoulder harnesses for the front seats.
The 1971 model year of Cessna 182 Skylane introduced improved cabin soundproofing.
The Cessna 182 Skylane was certified on 17 September 1969.
770 total Cessna 182 Skylane aircraft were built in the 1970-1971 period.
390 Cessna 182 Skylane aircraft were built in 1970.
380 Cessna 182 Skylane aircraft were built in 1971.
20 Cessna 182 Skylane aircraft were built by Argentina in 1972 as the A182N model.
The A182N model included the improvements of the 1972 182P model.
The Cessna 182P model was introduced for the 1972 model year.
The Cessna 182P featured cowling-mounted landing/taxi lights.
The Cessna 182P featured tubular steel main landing gear with increased track width.
The Cessna 182P featured "Camber-Lift" wings with a new leading edge.
The Cessna 182P featured a push-button annunciator panel.
The Cessna 182P featured redesigned control wheels.
The 1973 model year of Cessna 182P introduced bonded cowl and cabin doors.
The 1973 model year of Cessna 182P introduced a shock-mounted cowling.
The 1973 model year of Cessna 182P introduced an extended dorsal fairing.
The 1974 model year of Cessna 182P introduced tighter door/window seals.
The 1974 model year of Cessna 182P introduced new engine cooling baffle seals.
The 1974 model year of Cessna 182P introduced a constant-speed propeller.
The 1974 model year of Cessna 182P introduced optional 84 US gallon (320 liter) fuel tanks.
The 1974 model year of Cessna 182P introduced an optional oxygen system.

text:
The 1971 model year introduced shoulder harnesses for the front seats and improved cabin soundproofing.  Certified on 17 September 1969.  770 total built; 390 (1970) and 380 (1971), plus 20 built by Argentina in 1972 as the A182N with the improvements of that year's 182P.
182P
Introduced for the 1972 model year with cowling-mounted landing/taxi lights, tubular steel main landing gear with increased track width, "Camber-Lift" wings with a new leading edge, a push-button annunciator panel, and redesigned control wheels.  The 1973 model year introduced bonded cowl and cabin doors, a shock-mounted cowling, and an extended dorsal fairing.  1974 introduced tighter door/window seals, new engine cooling baffle seals, a constant-speed propeller, and optional 84 US gal (320 L) fuel tanks and oxygen system.
